# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Known off-label upstream surfaces
#
# Endpoints we depend on that were not designed as contracts for us. These are
# the likeliest things to break silently on an upstream bump, so they are
# listed separately from the version pin above. Re-check each when the version
# changes.
#
# 1. /health/detailed  -> "platforms" dict
#    Used by: Tasks lane (#156a, PR #135) as the source for the cron `deliver`
#    picker options. This is a DIAGNOSTIC endpoint being read for capability
#    discovery, so its shape is less likely than a real API to be treated as
#    stable upstream. Failure is graceful by design (picker degrades to free
#    text; unrecognised existing values are preserved as a "(custom)" row), so
#    a break is a UX regression, not data loss.
#
# 2. GET /api/jobs   -> requires ?include_disabled=true
#    Not off-label, but non-obvious: the default hides disabled jobs, so the
#    off/needsAttention states do not render without it. A future default
#    change here would silently alter which jobs the phone shows.
#
# 3. PATCH /api/jobs/{id} -> `repeat` MUST be sent as {times, completed}
#    Upstream merges updates with {**job, **updates} and performs no
#    normalisation, while the scheduler reads repeat.get("times"). Sending a
#    bare int replaces the dict and throws on the next scheduler pass. This is
#    host-side breakage caused by a client mistake — treat the dict form as
#    load-bearing, not stylistic.
